1.c: Railroad to south, but it is much lower than area.
1.b: All utilities. Fair transportation. St. Joseph's Catholic School and good public school.

areaDesc.5: Kown as Pigeon Hill. Many people of foreign birth. Adjacent to Quincy R.R. shops to southwest. Where many of these men find employment also in the Western-Austin Co. to east. Poor maintenance in some places. Age and obsolescence becoming heavy.

1.c: None except no paving and slow in developing.
1.b: All utilities. Just completing a new water system - village owned. Good school to south.

areaDesc.5: The sewer system is in the Aurora Sanitary District. A tourist camp is ocated between the railroad and highway on north. Noth of this area but outside of village limits is a slow developing high class neighborhood with nothing undesirable between here and Batavia. Many aurora people reside here. Majority of families are original purchasers.

1.b: Zoned for residential purposes only. Adjacent to good schols, on northeast and west. All utilities are in.

areaDesc.5: The development of the first high class homes on west side of Fox River occured here 40 years ago - on the north and east some properties are developing into income groups. Higher priced homes are on north. Well built up. Very heavily trood. Lawns and shrubbery well kept.

1.d: Odor from sheep yards to north.
1.b: In the Aurora Sanitary District. Lincoln Grade School to north. Transportation Fair.

areaDesc.5: The Village is limited on north by industry, cemetery and sheep yards; and on west by highway and main line Burlington R.R.; and on south by Sanitary disposal Plant. A declining village. No demand for property.

1.b: All public utilities. Adjacent to good schools, including West High to south.

areaDesc.5: Colored people moving in. Industry to west. Poor maintenance. Low income groups. The area is on downward grade rapidly, The colored people in this area are of better grade than usual.

1.b: All public utilties and schools - Good bus transportation. Nancy L. Hill public school in northwest.

areaDesc.5: Desirable residential section, but older than the "A" areas, well built up. Stable population. Majority of families are original purchasers.

1.c: None, except industry and at time odors from sheep yards to west.
1.b: Has all public utilties. Fair transportation. Good public school.

areaDesc.5: Workers in this area are close to their various places of employ-ment. There is a good public school in the sparsely settled east side. Homes are not well kept up, but the foreign element hang on to them and would not live elsewhere. A low income group. Spotted.

1.b: All utilities. Zoned. Fair transportation. West High School, Holy Angels School and good grade schools.

areaDesc.5: Funds for building and purchase are ample if credit risk of applicant is O.K. On north side of Falena Blvd. from Elmwood to Lancaster is a business district. Center part of area is oldest and many people of Sweish descent live here. The section on north of Plum is slowly declining, due to colored people on west. Heavily wooded.

1.b: Has all public utilities. Fair transportation. Adjacent to good schools on south.

areaDesc.5: Low income group coming in. Unpaved streets has retarded good type of construction and many garage cottages have been built, awaiting future development. Spotted. Maintenance is only fair. Demand for home ownership poor.

1.c: Majority unpaved streets and interspersed with industry. Sheep yard odors to the south.
1.b: All public utilties, and transportation good. Lincoln School in center of area.

areaDesc.5: North of Walnut is about 100% occupied and adjoins many coal yards. That section west of the Stephens-Adamson Manufacturing Co, is outside the city limits. That section south of Rathbone has been influenced by withdrawing of Standard Gass Equipment Co. and not as desirable to live in as other sections of area. This scattered area is in the midst of industry. Maintenance poor, and low income group.

1.c: Very little paving. Intersected by industry.
1.b: All utilities. Good transportation. Good grade school.

areaDesc.5: Settlement begun here in 1848. Majority of people living here work in Aurora. There is no demand for property. Age and obselescence heavy, but rents are always in demand.

1.c: None except state highway #71 on north. Factory and railroad to east.
1.b: All utilities. Good school and adequate transportation. Very well maintained, beautiful and lawns. Aurora College and Freeman School in area.

2.a: Business & professional. High class factory workers.

areaDesc.5: Two new subdivision to west have building restrictions and the area herein described is also restricted, although there are some garage bungalows or cottages on rear of a few lots, built 10-15 years ago - all zoned for residences. Very stable population. Trend of growth is in this direction. East of Commonwealth are many stone and brick residences with a 35 foot building line restriction. A very uniform and stable neighborhood.

1.b: All utilities. Good transportation. Good schools including East High School. Close to business district.

areaDesc.5: Include every type of zoned classification. Spotted. Kown as German Lutheran territory. From 5th Ave. North is oldest part of Aurora. Convenient to business and industry. South 4th St. is best street on east side. The section south of North from Jackson St. to east is a somewhat better grade than balance of area. This is one of the older sections of Aurora. Well treed. Many fine old homes are going into income property when necessary. Obsoles-cence heavy.

1.b: Has all public utilties. Close to business section.

areaDesc.5: Close in. Broadway at one time was a very fine street. This area was one of the earliest sections in Aurora. Poor maintenance. Majority of influences are detrimental to home ownership. Low income group. Age is taking its toll.

1.b: Best grade school and Catholic grade school are located in this area. All utiities. Close in to business district

areaDesc.5: All zoned - no now business houses can be erected in this area. Was a first grade district. 20 years ago - stil quite desirable. A distinctly German settlement east of 5th St. Opportunity for much further development does not exist. Spotted. A well settled old district in which rental demand is good. Sales demand has simmered down.

1.b: All public utitlies put in before any building. Good school and transportation excellent. Beautiful trees, with well-kept lawns and shrubbery. Public school to immediate west.

areaDesc.5: High percentage of home ownership. A comparatively new and restricted area. Land immediately north is farm property - well planned district - uniform and very desirable - expansion to north is limited at present due to a will which allows the executer to use his discretion in sub-dividing and which is to provide for an old ladies home. North of A-1 outside city limits is the North Lake Manor subdivision which has its own private water system. It also has gas and electricity, but no sewer. This subdivision is approximately 12 years old, but slowly developing. Six new homes have been built in the past 12 months in the $4000-4500 price range with FHA money. There is a probability at some future date of this subdivision connecting up with A-1. There are homes scattered all over this subdivision.

1.c: Industrial activity and railroad to east.
1.b: Fair transportation. All utilities. Marion Fox Valley Catholic High School (Boys).

2.a: Mixed, Business and professional on Lake St.

areaDesc.5: Percentage of high class houses, small and for most part located on Lake St. No restrictions. Age and absolescence creeping in. Cemetery in center of area.

1.b: Has all public utilities. Good grade schools.

areaDesc.5: An old development and due to adjacency to railroad shops desirable for laboring class. Low income groups live here. Many foreigners - infiltration of lower grade population. An old declining district whic has seen its best days.

1.c: Nothing particular with the exception of industry to the west
1.b: Has all public utilties. Fair bus transportation. Good SChools, including Madonna High (for girls)

areaDesc.5: Colored people around Kane, fulton, Pond Ave. and Trask St., also on North along R.R. Streets are mostly paved. A low priced area. One of the older districts of Aurora with many American-born foreigners of mixed nationalities. A low income community, but percentage of home ownership high. Obsolescence heavy. Well treed.
